histologic sections showed that halofuginone significantly reduced fibrosis
relative to the untreated control rats. We conclude that halofuginone is a
potent <I>in vivo</I> inhibitor of bleomycin&#150;induced pulmonary fibrosis,
and that it may potentially be used as a novel therapeutic agent for the
treatment of this dysfunction. <B>Nagler A, Firman N, Feferman R, Cotev S,
